title: For Sale:  polytech m14 308 (m1a)
postcontent:
This is a used polytech m14s in 7.62x51/308
Its got a beat up rattle-can camo job on it. 
Comes with 5 20 round mags, a sling, and a rifle case.
Its in great shape mechanically and works every time.
Neverbhad an issue except once with a cheapo magazine.
I tossed that mag in the trash and havent had a failure since.
Has probably ... 1000 rounds through it.  Give or take 100.
This rifle has a better reciever than a springfeild.  Its a forged reciever.  If you dont know how that is an upgrade research it.
These guns are notorious for reliability and theyre lretty damn accurate.
I usually get about 2 moa (typical of any m1a/m14) but i have lulled the occasional 1-1.5 moa 5 shot group.
If you take your time and the wind is still it can be done.
As you know these can fet into sub moa pretty easily if youre willing to spend the time and $.
Unfortunately, i dont have much of either.
And I don't want to see this rifle get neglected.
She can hunt she can plink she can fight.  One of the best rifles ever created.
$900.
I know you can spend 400 more and get a springfeild 16" but trust me... this is the one you want.
These cant be imported any more and theyre somebof the best m14s available at the best prices.
Without any cases or mags or slings you can maybe find one of these forb $800 if youre willing to wait around a year searching dilligently daily for one.
But likely you wont.
These are getting rare so i know what its worth. Dont low-ball me please.  This rifle is the only way youre getting into an m14/m1a for under $1100.
I will get pictures when i have time.  
All cash offers welcome.
Not interested in trades right now.

title: For Sale:  Truglo Fiber Optic/Night Sights for Sig Sauer
postcontent:
For Sig Sauer classic P Series pistols in 9/40. Night sights still glow, the front sight glows slightly more than the rear sights.

Truglo TFO`s are night sights that incorporate fiber optic light pipes. When I describe these sights to my customers, I let them now they are the brightest sights available for use at night or during the day. These sights are truly a 24 hour lighting system. When there is any ambient light available, the fiber optic light pipes gather that light and channel it to the rear where your eyes pick it up. The sights also have built in vials of tritium like any other night sights.  These are always emitting a glow. What makes the TFO`s so special is that those tritium vials are buried in front of the fiber optics. When there is not enough outside light available for the fiber optics to pick up, the glow from the tritium is then channeled to the users eyes. These sights use multiple technologies to gather enough light, day or night to be one of the most useful sets of sights available on the market.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster P97S 7.5" carbon pistol upper w/ MB, #AZ15133 threaded adapter & chging handle
postcontent:
Here's something different. These uppers were _never sold separately_ by Bushmaster; you had to buy the complete pistol, which retailed for $1049 and typically sold for $700-$800. 

See more pics here: http://www.ar15.com/mobile/topic.html?b=7&f=118&t=1463516

I am original owner of this minty upper, which is a take-off from a P97S pistol that I SBR'ed in 2005. The pistol S/N is D068** (you can fit a free-float handguard to this upper if you like, because the barrel nut diameter is AR standard on this S/N range). The P97S was Bushmaster's top-of-the-line rework of the old Professional Ordnance guns, and it runs great. This upper takes any standard AR BCG. 

_Also included_ is the original quick-detach muzzle brake, the original charging handle, and the discontinued #AZ15133 threaded adapter, which swaps out with the quick-detach muzzle brake to fit any 1/2 x 28 TPI accessories you may wish to use. It weighs less than 2.25 lbs. all together. 

_Not included_: BCG.

Pictured below is how I had the upper setup on my SBR; I ran the threaded adapter to an AAC 18T blackout MB to the AAC 762-SD, which worked great. Without a suppressor, this barrel length produces a massive fireball and concussion. 

I've gotten out and shot this maybe 5x times in 10x years, the pictures speak for themselves. I am parting the SBR out because resale transfer fees are prohibitive ($400 total), and I am trying a 10.5" upper now. Price includes S&H to your door -- ppal + 3% or USPS MO both accepted, check my feedback under this username on both eBay & GB. 

"The P97S Upper Receiver features a full length anodized aluminum Picatinny rail that includes integral front and rear iron sights. The windage adjustable rear sight is a combination ghost ring and precision aperture flip-up. The square post front sights offers elevation adjustments for fine zeroing. The Picatinny rail allows the option of mounting a wide variety of auxiliary sighting systems such as long eye relief and standard scopes, red dot, holographic, or laser sights. A similar rail extends the full length of the bottom of the hand guard allowing for the attachment of flashlights and accessories. The pistol’s stainless steel, match grade barrel is chambered for the 5.56 NATO cartridge and readily accepts the .223 Remington cartridge as well."
